What changed in V2

1. The Cross-Encoder now reranks all useful candidates

The earlier architecture could rerank semantic-memory candidates, but it did not always rerank the complete union of:

supervised ML candidates
semantic-memory candidates
adaptive-memory partial candidates
dictionary alternatives

V2 merges these into an internal candidate pool of up to 24 codes and reranks the combined pool. The public .sav and log can still expose the top four.

This is important because the correct code may be found by Linear SVC even when FAISS does not retrieve it, or vice versa.

2. The Cross-Encoder is fine-tuned on your task

The generic MS MARCO Cross-Encoder was trained for general information retrieval, not for distinguishing neighboring SOC or NAICS codes.

V2 creates task-specific training pairs from your historical coded data:

Positive:
survey context + correct code description
Hard negatives:
survey context + confused code in the same SOC/NAICS hierarchy
Semantic negatives:
survey context + highly similar but incorrect candidate
Random negatives:
survey context + unrelated code

Hard negatives are particularly useful because they teach the model distinctions such as:

registered nurse vs licensed practical nurse
bookkeeper vs accountant
retail supervisor vs retail salesperson
software developer vs computer systems analyst
construction laborer vs operating engineer

The trainer mixes hard and random negatives because training only on extremely difficult negatives can harm easy-case discrimination. Sentence Transformers’ training guidance emphasizes hard-negative mining while also retaining suitable negative diversity.  

The trainer also oversamples the weak SOC major groups identified in your audit:

qe4ar: 15, 17, 25, 51, 55
qe5ar: 15, 17, 45, 51, 53, 55

3. A separate calibration dataset is now required

Your permanent Gold file stays untouched.

The prior training_MODEL.sav is divided into:

training_FIT.sav
training_CALIBRATION.sav

Their roles are:

FIT:
train classifiers, semantic memory, adaptive memory, and the Cross-Encoder
CALIBRATION:
learn candidate-fusion weights, confidence calibration, and conformal thresholds
GOLD:
final untouched comparison only

This separation matters because a calibrator evaluated on the same records used to fit it will look better than it really is. Scikit-learn’s calibration documentation recommends disjoint fitting and calibration data, and warns that isotonic calibration can overfit on small calibration samples. V2 uses isotonic only when support is sufficient and otherwise uses sigmoid calibration.  

4. Candidate fusion is learned rather than hand-weighted

The previous system used fixed weights for ML probability, semantic similarity, and Cross-Encoder score.

V2 trains a small candidate-level stacking model using calibration data. Its inputs include:

supervised model score
semantic-memory score
Cross-Encoder score
candidate rank
adaptive-memory evidence
dictionary evidence
prefix compatibility
prediction-source flags

It learns how these signals should be combined separately for:

qa20a
qe4ar
qe5ar

This directly addresses the apples-and-oranges problem of adding SVM margins, cosine similarities, and transformer logits using fixed weights.

5. Confidence is calibrated separately by source

The audit proved that sources behave very differently:

adaptive exact: around 98% accurate
dictionary: around 95% to 97% accurate
model-only SOC: around 45% accurate

One universal confidence mapping is therefore inappropriate.

V2 calibrates confidence according to prediction source, so a 0.90 score from an adaptive exact rule is not treated identically to a 0.90 converted SVM margin.

6. APS conformal prediction sets are added

V2 can calculate a smallest plausible set of codes for a requested empirical coverage level.

For example:

Row A: {291141}
Row B: {131072, 131199}
Row C: {472061, 472079, 499071}

This is more defensible than pretending every row has one certain answer. APS and RAPS are established conformal methods for constructing multiclass prediction sets using calibration data.  

The audit reports:

empirical coverage
average prediction-set size
median set size
90th-percentile set size
coverage by target and subgroup

7. The semantic memory now stores code prototypes

Instead of relying only on thousands of raw historical examples, V2 creates representative per-code prototypes from examples closest to each code’s embedding centroid.

This gives the Cross-Encoder cleaner candidate evidence and reduces the chance that one odd historical wording becomes the sole representative of a code.

